The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Shimla, Sept. 28 (PTI): Himachal Pradesh University yesterday decided to recommend a vigilance probe against former vice-chancellor Anil Wilson for investing Rs 3.4 crore from the general provident fund without the executive councils permission.           
	Wilson had served as principal of St Stephens College.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Utsav Bhasin, accused of killing a person while driving his BMW, was on Sunday sent to judicial custody till October 10 by a Delhi court. Bhasin, a business mans son has refused to undergo a test-identification parade. His application for anticipatory bail had been rejected.                  
	 Chandigarh (PTI): An object that looked like a firecracker, set off a scare at Bankerpura in Punjab near the Ambala-Delhi highway on Sunday, police said. Army experts have been called in to check the object.                   
	 Karimnagar (PTI): Three debt-ridden weavers committed suicide on Saturday at Sircilla in this district, police said. At least six weavers have committed suicide in the Andhra district in the past fortnight.                  
	 Thimphu (PTI): A new entry and exit point on the India-Bhutan frontier will soon come up in Phuentsholing to ease traffic in the border town. The tentative position of the gate is near the State Trading Corporation of Bhutan in lower Phuentsholing.                   
	 Jammu (PTI): Jammu and Kashmir governor N. N. Vohra on Sunday laid the foundation stone for the LoC trade centre in Poonch district. India and Pakistan have agreed to start cross-border business from October 28.                                                                                                                          
